{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> κνίζω</b>, <br /> <i>future</i> κνίσω [ῐ] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 1198 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἔκνῐσα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 8.32, 3rd c.BC: Herodas Mimographus 4.59, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Doric dialect</i> ἔκνιξα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 6(5).50 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <i>aorist</i> ἐκνίσθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 209, 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 4.59 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <b>scratch, gash</b>, παῖδα.. γυμνὸν ἢν κνίσω.. οὐχ ἕλκος ἕξε; Herod.[same place]; κνίζων συκάμινα (to make them ripen) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Amos.7.14, compare 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 2.51b. \">LXX+2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>pound, chop up</b>, or <b>grate</b>, uncertain in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 9.20.4 (perhaps κνησθεῖσα). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>tickle</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 587b7 (_passive_), 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “περὶ παρρησίας” p.58 O. (_passive_). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> usually <i>metaphorically</i>, of love, <b>chafe, tease</b>, τὸν Ἀρίστωνα ἔκνιζε τῆς γυναικὸς ταύτης ἔρως [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.62, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 568; κἠγὼ μὰν κνίζω τινά 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 5.122 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of other feelings, as satiety, κόρος κνίζει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” [same place]; anxiety, Ξέρξην ἔκνιζε ἡ γνώμη 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.12; τὰ σμικρὰ οὐδέν μιν κνίζει (i.e. τὸν θεόν) [prev. work] 10 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>].; ἔκνιζέ μ᾽ αἰεὶ τοῦθ᾽ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 786; τὸ βούλεσθαί μ᾽ ἔκνιζε 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Aulidensis” 330 (troch.)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>provoke, tease</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 1286 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐ κατ᾽ ἔπος κνίσω τὸ ῥῆμ᾽ ἕκαστον <b>will</b> not <b>attack</b> every word, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. author] “Ra.” \">Refs</a>][same place]; <b>provoke to jealousy</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Alciphro Epistolographus 1.32 \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]; in good sense, ἁδεῖά νιν ἔκνιξε χάρις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 6(5).50 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 555, “Andr.” [same place]; ἐρωτίδα τᾶς ποκ᾽ ἐκνίσθη 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 4.59, compare 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “DMeretr.” 10.4; κνιζόμενος ὑπ᾽ ἔρωτος ἐπὶ τῇ παιδί 2nd c.AD: Appianus Historicus “Αιβυκή” 10 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐκνίσθη; <b>does that touch you</b>? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus “Περινθία” 16. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__II.2.b</b></Level4> <b>provoke</b>, ὀργὰν κνίζον αἰπεινοὶ λόγοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 5.32, compare “P.” 11.23. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8037","accentedUnicode":"κνίζω","shortDef":"to pick","mediumDef":"to pick","stepGloss":"to pick","stepTransliteration":"knizō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}